<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06318012 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06318012 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; HOCKEY; GAME; RESULT; SAN-JOSE; CHART  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Sharks didn't see Pat LaFontaine when they visited the Buffalo Sabres onOct. 25, and they would have been happy if LaFontaine had been someplace otherthan the Cow Palace on Tuesday night.;   LaFontaine, obtained by the Sabres ina seven-player trade with the New York Islanders on the day the Sharks visitedBuffalo, scored his eighth career hat trick to lead the Sabres to a 7-1victory over the Sharks before another Cow Palace sellout of 10,888.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  LAFONTAINE LEADS SABRES TO EASY WIN OVER SHARKS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;We gave him a lot of opportunities, and he gave an indication of why he'sone of the best players in the league,&quot; Sharks Coach George Kingston said.&quot;When you're facing a player like that, you have to make sure that you'reconcentrating on playing good defense.&quot;;   LaFontaine didn't arrive in Buffaloin time to face the Sharks in the first meeting between the teams, which theSabres won 3-1. But his presence in the rematch helped make life easy forSabres goalie Tom Draper, who was pressed into duty when Daren Puppa suffereda broken bone in his left forearm during the Buffalo's morning practicesession.;   Draper, who was making his first start of the season and ninthcareer NHL appearance, stopped 41 of the 42 shots he faced to hand the Sharks(3-16) their first loss in three games. The 42 shots by the Sharks were aseason high.;   The Sabres received two goals from Donald Audette and singlescores from Doug Bodger and Randy Wood. Alexander Mogilny had three assistsfor the Sabres. Pat Falloon scored a power-play goal off assists from DavidBruce and David Williams for the Sharks.;   After scoring once in the firstperiod and once in the second, LaFontaine completed his hat trick by scoringon a breakaway after only 39 seconds had expired in the third period. Thegoal, LaFontaine's fifth of the season, gave the Sabres a 5-0 lead.;   &quot;I knewit was just a matter of time before good things started happening,&quot; LaFontainesaid. &quot;It's exciting to make that kind of contribution.&quot;;   Goalie Arturs Irbemade his third consecutive start for the Sharks but was removed after givingup three goals in the first period. Irbe, who won his first two NHL startslast week, was replaced by Jeff Hackett at the start of the second period.;  &quot;We were trying to get the team to wake up and get into the game,&quot; Kingstonsaid when asked why he made the goalie switch. &quot;When you make a change likethat, you're just trying to send a signal to the team that you're trying togive them a new start.&quot;;   The Sabres (6-9-1) got off to a good start byscoring on three of their first eight shots.;   &quot;It was important for us toget ahead early and take the crowd out of the game,&quot; LaFontaine said. &quot;Weneeded a big victory, and we'll take these two points.&quot;; Buffalo   3 1 3 -- 7;San Jose  0 0 1 -- 1;   FIRST PERIOD -- 1, Buffalo, LaFontaine 3 (May,Mogilny), 5:29. 2, Buffalo, Bodger 3 (Patterson, Ray), 11:00. 3, Buffalo, Wood5 (Ruuttu, Sutton), 15:38. Penalties -- Haller, Buf (holding), 2:46; Presley,SJ (interference), 13:30.;   SECOND PERIOD -- 4, Buffalo, LaFontaine 4(Haller, May), 17:41. Penalties -- Bodger, Buf (high-sticking), 7:49; May, Buf(roughing), 10:43.;   THIRD PERIOD -- 5, Buffalo, LaFontaine 5 (Mogilny,Sutton), :39. 6, Buffalo, Audette 7 (Hawerchuk, Haller), 4:51. 7, San Jose,Falloon 4 (Bruce, Williams), 7:53 (pp). 8, Buffalo, Audette 8 (Mogilny),11:12. Penalties -- Wood, Buf, major (fighting), 5:42; Evason, SJ, major(fighting), 5:42; Miller, Buf (cross-checking), 7:07; Hawerchuk, Buf, tripleminor (high-sticking, double unsportsmanlike conduct), 9:05; Presley, SJ,double minor (slashing, roughing), 9:05; Ray, Buf, major (fighting), 12:14;McGill, SJ, major (fighting), 12:14; May, Buf, major (fighting), 17:11; Wood,Buf, double minor (roughing), 17:11; Miller, Buf, double minor (roughing),17:11; Presley, SJ, double minor (roughing), 17:11; Anderson, SJ (roughing),17:11; Lawton, SJ, double minor (high-sticking, roughing), 17:11; Donnelly,Buf (roughing), 19:20; Anderson, SJ (roughing), 19:20.;   SHOTS ON GOAL --Buffalo 15-7-8 -- 30. San Jose 12-17-13 -- 42.;   POWER-PLAY OPPORTUNITIES --Buffalo 0 of 1; San Jose 1 of 6.;   GOALIES -- Buffalo, Draper, 1-0-0 (42shots-41 saves). San Jose, Irbe, 2-1-0 (15-12), Hackett (0:00 second, 15-11).;  ATT. -- 10,888.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  MIKE WEAVER, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911113  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  CHART  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  723  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, November 13, 199100318012,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>